Cytomegalovirus (CMV) is a common virus that can infect people of all ages. It is usually harmless and may not cause any symptoms in healthy individuals. However, CMV can cause serious complications in people with weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS, organ transplant recipients, and newborn babies.

Symptoms of CMV infection can include fever, fatigue, sore throat, and swollen glands. In severe cases, CMV can lead to pneumonia, hepatitis, and other serious health issues.

Treatment for CMV infection may include antiviral medications, particularly for individuals with weakened immune systems. Prevention strategies include practicing good hygiene, avoiding contact with bodily fluids from infected individuals, and getting vaccinated if available.

In conclusion, understanding the risks and symptoms of CMV infection is important for individuals with weakened immune systems and healthcare providers to effectively manage and prevent complications associated with this virus.
